title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}=(a_{i,j})]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {B}=(b_{i,j})]]></fr:tex> be two <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrices. We define their <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Difference</html:dfn> to be the matrix <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}-\mathbf {B} = \mathbf {A} + -1\cdot \mathbf {B}]]></fr:tex>. This gives us the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Matrix Subtraction</html:dfn> binary operator on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrices.</fr:p><fr:p>Similarly, the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">(Matrix) Negation</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> is the matrix <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[-\mathbf {A}=-1\cdot \mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>. This is a unary operator on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrices.</fr:p>
 
   
